  READ DOCUMENTATION CAREFULY (it is highly recomended to use suplied 
 @{"Install" link "Install" } script), becouse door will not function well if
 some files are missing ! (may be it even cause Mr.Gurru???)

@endnode

@node "Require" "MV Status - Requirements"
@next "install"
@prev "disclaim"
    
                      @{b}Door requirements@{ub}
                      ----------------- 

You need Amiga OS and DayDream 1.27 or higher (door is using HideCursor
& ShowCursor functions of dreamdoor.library, and those functions
are implemented in version 1.27 and later).

Some Disk_cache utility is recomended, becouse door acces few files very 
often, and standard Amiga DOS Buffers doesent work too nice.


@endnode

@node "Install" " MV Status - Instalation "
@next "Features"
@prev "Require"


 It is highly recomended to use supplied INSTALL script for instaling 
MV STATUS Door. To use it, simply unpack archive (you have to extract 
archive with enabled "Extract files with full path" option!) on any device,
enter this diretory from shell and type INSTALL. (make sure that Doors: 
directory is already assigned, otherwise install script will fail!)

If operation is finished succesfuly, install script will write following
message :
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
        Mad Virgin STATUS door V1.00B for DayDream BBS - AMIGA !
                                                               (26.04.1997)

 INSTALATION OK !

 PLEASE READ THE DOCS !!!!
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
and return you to main prompt.

After that, add in your DayDream folowing lines to EXTERNALCOMMANDS.DAT
+
DOOR_COMMAND.. STAT
DOOR_TYPE..... 1
DOOR_SECURITY. 5
DOOR_EXECUTE.. Doors:MV/STAT/MVStat %N
DOOR_CONFS1... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
DOOR_CONFS2... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
+


@endnode

@node "Features" " MV Status - Features "
@next "Config"
@prev "Install"

 MV Status door allow you to create three diferent STATUS pages.

 In fact you may configure 4 diferent outlooks for MV STAT.

        - ISO
        - ISO + ANSI 
        - IBM
        - IBM + ANSI

 Look at @{"Configuration" Link Config} section for details.


@endnode

@node Config "MV Status - Configuration"
@next "User"
@prev "Features"

                  @{bg shine}»»»»»»»» CONFIGURATION ««««««««««@{bg back}

   The MV Status Door is consist of two parts need to be configured to
   match your system configuration :

           @{"   STAT.CFG  " link stat.cfg }

           @{" DISPLAY.CFG " link display.cfg}

 After that you may start configuring (if you want?) files in 
 Doors:MV/STAT/Display directory.

As you can see, there are several files with same name and diferent extension.
Yes, you are right - MV STAT uses these files for outlook.

 In fact, there are folowing groups of display files :

  item-*.*                                     - main status outlook file
       | |
       | |___item mode (ASCII/TXT/ISO/IBM)
       |
       |
       item number : 1 to 3

       
   button*-sel.*                                - gadgets in ANSI mode
         |     |
         |     |____ gadget mode (IBM/ISO)
         |
         |___ gadget number : 1 to 4


   selection.*                                  - menu prompt in ASCII mode
             |
             |____ menu mode (ASCII/TXT)


   header.*                                     - header file in ANSI mode
          |
          |____ header mode (ISO/IBM)


   footer.*                                     - footer file in ANSI mode
          |
          |____ footer  mode (ISO/IBM)


Change files to match your wishes.
Anywhere in files you may put prefix @{b}&@{ub} and after that one of
following marks: 

Mark    Means                           Size

USER PERSONAL INFO :
Q   - User Real name                    25
W   - User Handle                       25
E   - User Organization                 25
R   - user ZIP & City                   25
T   - user Voice phone no.              20
Y   - user Screen lenght                 3
U   - user Protocol ID                  20
L   - user Computer model               21
O   - user UL Signature                 45
C   - user Security level                3
F   - user No of msg.w.to all            6
G   - user No of other wr.msg.           6
0   - user total messages writen         6
H   - user Calls to system               5
X   - user Failed logins                 3
B   - user Date of first call           15
N   - user Date of last call            15
V   - user Conference to join            3
M   - user Daily time limit              3
3   - user Slot number                   5
4   - user Remaining daily time          3
        
FILE RELATED INFO :        
J   - user File ratio                    3
K   - user Byte ratio                    3
S   - user UL files                     10
P   - user UL bytes                     10
D   - user DL files                     10
A   - user DL bytes                     10
5   - user Free DL files                 5
Z   - user FREE DL bytes                10
6   - user Faked files                   5
7   - user Faked bytes                  10
-   - files left                        10
\   - bytes left                        10


GENERAL SYSTEM INFO :
[   - Board name                        26
]   - Sysop name                        26
a   - Idle timeout time                  3
s   - Connection BPSRATE                 6
d   - I/O device name                   25
8   - free CHIP MEM                     10
9   - free FAST MEM                     10
=   - total free MEM                    10
        
CURENT CONFERENCE INFO :        
q   - Conference number                  3
w   - Conference name                   40
e   - No. of fileareas in conf           3
r   - UL area in conf.                   3
t   - No. of msg bases                   3
        
CURENT MESSAGE BASE INFO :
y   - Base number                        3
u   - Base name                         21
i   - Base FIDO TAG                     26
o   - Base FIDO ORIGIN                  58
p   - Base FIDO ADDRESS                 19


Just take care NOT TO PUT any ansi code in area which will be covered
by size of &Information !!!!!! If you do so, the output will be screwed
up! :(
Also, ALWAYS leave empty spaces before CR (carrige return) for item
to be outputed (leave as many spaces as & item is long!)


@endnode


@node "stat.cfg" "MV Stat - Configuration - STAT.CFG "
@prev config
@next display.cfg

Stat cfg must consist of folowing lines!
Please, take care and do not mess order of lines or door will screw up!
Simply edit lines in exsisting CFG file!

X1Coo... 2      - upper left X of ANSI mode stat window 0 < x1 <= 79
Y2Coo... 5      - upper left Y of ANSI mode stat window 3 < y1 <= 18
X2Coo... 78     - lower right X of ANSI mode stat wind. x1< x2 <= 79
Y2Coo... 16     - lower right Y of ANSI mode stat wind. y1< y2 <= 30
GAD1X... 4      - Gadget 1 (for ANSI display) X position
GAD1Y... 18     - Gadget 1 (for ANSI display) Y position
GAD2X... 26     - Gadget 2 (for ANSI display) X position
GAD2Y... 18     - Gadget 2 (for ANSI display) Y position
GAD3X... 48     - Gadget 3 (for ANSI display) X position
GAD3Y... 18     - Gadget 3 (for ANSI display) Y position
GAD4X... 71     - Gadget 4 (for ANSI display) X position
GAD4Y... 18     - Gadget 4 (for ANSI display) Y position
BG_COL3. [40m  - BGND ANSI code for CLEAR routine in ISO ANSI mode (10 char MAX!)
BG_COL4. [44m  - BGND ANSI code for CLEAR routine in IBM ANSI mode (10 char MAX!)
CLS..... N      - CLS in ASCII/TXT mode (modes 1 & 2) - MUST be Y or N !
EFFECT.. N      - Effect when refreshing screen in ANSI modes  ( Y or N )         


@endnode

@node display.cfg "MV Stat - Configuration - dISPLAY.CFG"
@prev stat.cfg
@next Config

In this file you must enter as many items as you have display modes on
your BBS.

This means that if you have 6 display modes, your display.cfg will look
something like this :
------------cut here --------------------
2
1
1
3
4
4
------------cut here --------------------

Number means that display mode is :

1 - ISO                 ( ISO charset - NO ANSI commands )
2 - IBM                 ( IBM charset - NO ANSI commands )
3 - ISO + ANSI          ( ISO charset - ANSI codes supported ) 
4 - IBM + ANSI          ( IBM charset - ANSI codes supported ) 

Please, carefully edit lines to match your display modes configuration.
(first line is for display mode 1, second is for mode 2.... etc...)

If you think that there can be something else added, please contact @{"author" Link author}


@endnode


